paragraphs.text:
%md
###1. Initialize the Cache Magic, and show the basic statistics
Please specify:  
**[cache file]:** it is got used Ycap, stored on hdfs(hdfs://..) or local file system of every spark worker(file://..); 
**[pool Info file (optional)]:** which tell Magic that server/client IpPort belong to the pools. Both file should be in Hdfs.
__the format of poolInfo file is like(each line a pool,):__
poolname1 ip1:port1,ip2:port2,ip3:port3,...,
poolname2 ip1:port1,ip2:port2,ip3:port3,...,
**The filter condition:**
**[filter of key]**: A filter for key. if the format is /reg exp/, it match as a regular expression; otherwise match as sub-string.
**[poolname]**: A filter for poolName. if the format is /reg exp/, it match as a regular expression; otherwise match as sub-string.
**[precision]**: The precision of time. e.g. 1: 0.1 second; 2:0.01 second; 3: 0.001 second and so on.
**[outputLimit]**: The default limitation of output for web display.
**[start time / end time]**: the time range of data you want to analyze.

paragraphs.title: Init a magic instance with yCap and poolInfo files in hadoop
paragraphs.text:
import com.yhd.ycache.magic._
val magic = new Magic(sc,z.input("1 cache file","hdfs://heju:8020/user/root/magic/log.0318").toString,z.input("2 pool Info","").toString)
def initMagic(magic: Magic) = {
    magic.startTime = z.input("3 start time","1970/01/01 00:00:00").toString
    magic.endTime   = z.input("4 end time","2016/01/01 12:00:00").toString
    magic.precision = z.input("5 precision","1").toString.toInt
    magic.outputLimit = z.input("6 outputLimit","50000").toString.toInt
    magic.load(z.input("7 poolName filter","all").toString,z.input("8 key filter","all").toString)
    magic.createTable()
}  
initMagic(magic)
